> >
> > My efforts to find a "pristine" single cab split truck had gone nowhere.
> >
> > Good news today! A guy told me about a deluxe sitting in a home garage
in
> > North Carolina just 15 miles from here! I went to look and it is
> beautiful.
> > Her Chinese grandparents bought the bus to drive to the market in
> Asheville
> > for supplies for their restaurant. When the suppliers started delivering
> on
> > the early 1970's, the bus was parked inside. There is no rust on this
> thing
> > as it has been in the garage since then. It has faded a bit but not bad
> for
> > original paint. It might be older as she showed me a thingy to stick in
> the
> > rear to hand start the motor? Never seen that before.
> >
> > Anyway, I wonder where I need to make the cut to make it a single cab. I
> > might take it a little back and make a double cab "binz" whatever that
is.
> I
> > will need to cut some plywood just right to seal up the rear. Looks like
> > those upper windows might get in the way of the cutting. Any ideas about
> > what type of caulk to apply to the wood for a good seal?
> >
> > For $400.00, I cannot go wrong. I should be able to get some
measurements
> at
> > EveryBus but really want to start cutting! Please help with advice or
send
> > pictures. I have never seen a "real" single cab around here.
> >
> > Thanx!
> >
> > Ric Jablonski
> > Roan Mountain, TN
